# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: supply-chain-software
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The **bullwhip effect** is a supply chain phenomenon where orders to suppliers tend to have a larger variability than sales to buyers, which results in an amplified demand variability upstream.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In part, this results in increasing swings in inventory in response to shifts in consumer demand as one moves further up the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The concept first appeared in Jay Forrester's *Industrial Dynamics* (1961) and thus it is also known as the **Forrester effect**.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] It has been described as "the observed propensity for material orders to be more variable than demand signals and for this variability to increase the further upstream a company is in a supply chain".
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Research at Stanford University helped incorporate the concept into supply chain vernacular using a story about Volvo.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Suffering a glut in green cars, sales and marketing developed a program to sell the excess inventory.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] While successful in generating the desired market pull, manufacturing did not know about the promotional plans.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Instead, they read the increase in sales as an indication of growing demand for green cars and ramped up production.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Research indicates a fluctuation in point-of-sale demand of five percent will be interpreted by supply chain participants as a change in demand of up to forty percent.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Much like cracking a whip, a small flick of the wrist - a shift in point of sale demand - can cause a large motion at the end of the whip - manufacturers' responses.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Because customer demand is rarely perfectly stable, businesses must forecast demand to properly position inventory and other resources.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Forecasts are based on statistics, and they are rarely perfectly accurate.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Because forecast errors are expected, companies often carry an inventory buffer called "safety stock".
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Moving up the supply chain from end-consumer to raw materials supplier, each supply chain participant has greater observed variation in demand and thus greater need for safety stock.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In periods of rising demand, down-stream participants increase orders.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In periods of falling demand, orders fall or stop, thereby not reducing inventory.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The effect is that variations are amplified as one moves upstream in the supply chain (further from the customer).
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] This sequence of events is well simulated by the beer distribution game that was developed by MIT Sloan School of Management in the 1960s.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Research on supply-chain complexity has identified additional mechanisms through which variability may propagate through supply networks.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The "supply chain complexity triangle" describes uncertainty as arising from the interaction of demand amplification, deterministic chaos, and parallel interactions between supply-chain channels.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In addition to demand amplification, the framework highlights how disturbances may spread through interconnected channels and nonlinear feedback processes within the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The causes can further be divided into behavioral and operational causes.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The first theories focusing onto the bullwhip effect were mainly focusing on the irrational behavior of the human in the supply chain, highlighting them as the main cause of the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Since the 90's, the studies evolved, placing the supply chain's malfunctioning at the heart of their studies abandoning the human factors.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Previous control-theoretic models have identified as causes the tradeoff between stationary and dynamic performance as well as the use of independent controllers.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] (2017), one of the main behavioral causes that contribute to the bullwhip effect is the under-estimation of the pipeline.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In addition, the complementary bias, over-estimation of the pipeline, also has a negative effect under such conditions.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Nevertheless, it has been shown that when the demand stream is stationary, the system is relatively robust to this bias.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In such situations, it has been found that biased policies (both under-estimating and over-estimating the pipeline) perform just as well as unbiased policies.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Human factors influencing the behavior in supply chains are largely unexplored.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] However, studies suggest that people with increased need for safety and security seem to perform worse than risk-takers in a simulated supply chain environment.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] People with high self-efficacy experience less trouble handling the bullwhip-effect in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] (1997) study found that the bullwhip effect did not solely result from irrational decision making: it found that under some circumstances it is rational for a firm to order with greater variability than variability of demand, i.e., distort demand and cause the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] They established a list of four major factors which cause the bullwhip effect: demand signal processing, rationing game, order batching, and price variations.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] This list has become a standard and is used as a framework to identify bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In addition to greater safety stocks, the described effect can lead to either inefficient production or excessive inventory, as each producer needs to fulfill the demand of its customers in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] This also leads to a low utilization of the distribution channel.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In spite of having safety stocks there is still the hazard of stock-outs which result in poor customer service and lost sales.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In addition to the (financially) hard measurable consequences of poor customer services and the damage to public image and loyalty, an organization has to cope with the ramifications of failed fulfillment which may include contractual penalties.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Moreover, repeated hiring and dismissal of employees to manage the demand variability induces further costs due to training and possible lay-offs.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Since the Corona virus pandemic, many companies have been dealing with a strong bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] This problem is directly linked to the ongoing impacts of the Corona virus pandemic, even though it is further exacerbated by the ever changing nature of demand for consumer goods .
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] These shortages caused companies to order even more as they reasoned this would give them a larger share of the pie.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] As lead times return to normal, however, all these products are finally flowing in but demand drops for these same products leading to large excess inventory.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] In other words, retailers or customers order more based on slight sales increases or increases in demand, which causes each entity in the supply chain to request or produce more in anticipation of higher demands, at the end creating a ripple effect in the supply and logistics chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] For instance, during the pandemic, people suddenly bought lots of essential and safety-related goods like nose masks, hand sanitizers, causing big fluctuations in demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] As each level in the supply chain reacted to these extra demands, they tended to over-order to prevent stockouts, which made the problem worse down to the manufacturer.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] This led to excessive investment in inventory, lost revenue, declines in customer service, delayed schedules, and even layoffs or bankruptcies and global freight services delivery delays as was the case for e-commerce platforms like Amazon and Alibaba.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] During the COVID-19 pandemic, they faced global shipping delays, increased freight costs, and lead-time uncertainties.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] When shipping and production are delayed, downstream partners, retailers and consumers often order more just in case, thereby further enhancing the ripple effects of the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Information sharing across the supply chain is an effective strategy to mitigate the bullwhip effect.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] For example, it has been successfully implemented in Wal-Mart's distribution system.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Individual Wal-Mart stores transmit point-of-sale (POS) data from the cash register back to corporate headquarters several times a day.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] This demand information is used to queue shipments from the Wal-Mart distribution center to the store and from the supplier to the Wal-Mart distribution center.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The result is near-perfect visibility of customer demand and inventory movement throughout the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Better information leads to better inventory positioning and lower costs throughout the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Another recommended strategy to limit the bullwhip effect is order smoothing.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Previous research has demonstrated that order smoothing and the bullwhip effect are concurrent in industry.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] It has been proved that order smoothing is beneficial for the system's performance when the demand is stationary.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] However, its impact is limited to the worst-case order amplification when the demand is unpredictable.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Having said that, dynamic analysis reveals that order smoothing can degrade performance in the presence of demand shocks.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The opposite bias (i.e., over-reaction to mismatches), on the other hand, degrades the stationary performance but can increase dynamic performance; controlled over-reaction can aid the system reach its new goals quickly.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] The system, nevertheless, is considerably sensitive to that behaviour; extreme over-reaction significantly reduces performance.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Overall, unbiased policies offer in general good results under a large range of demand types.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Although these policies do not result in the best performance under certain criteria.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] It is always possible to find a biased policy that outperforms an unbiased policy for any one performance metric.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Many studies demonstrate the bullwhip effect in a supply chain from different perspectives, including information sharing, information distortion, bankruptcy events and systematic risk.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Most of them devote themselves to exploring the bullwhip effect from the perspectives of inventory flow risk and information flow risk rather than that of cash flow risk.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] For a firm's internal liquidity risk (Chen et al., 2011), it is an appropriate proxy for a firm's financial risk.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] This is more generally modelled in Proselkov's work in 2023, which uses complex adaptive systems modelling to study cascade failures as a consequence of financial bullwhips.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] Specifically, they create an agent-based supply network simulation model capturing the behaviours of companies with asymmetric power dynamics with their partners.
[src:supply-chain-software/bullwhip-effect] To remain operational, they maximise their liquidity by negotiating longer repayment terms and cheaper financing, thus distributing risk onto weaker companies and propagating financial stress.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Demand forecasting may be used in resource allocation, inventory management, assessing future capacity requirements, or making decisions on whether to enter a new market.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Customer demand planning (CDP) is a business planning process that allows sales teams to develop demand forecasts.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Demand forecasting plays an important role for businesses in different industries, particularly with regard to mitigating the risks associated with particular business activities.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] However, demand forecasting is known to be a challenging task for businesses due to the intricacies of analysis, specifically quantitative analysis.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Nevertheless, understanding customer needs is an indispensable part of any industry in order for business activities to be implemented efficiently and more appropriately respond to market needs.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] If businesses are able to forecast demand effectively, several benefits can be accrued.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] These include, but are not limited to, waste reduction, optimized allocation of resources, and potentially large increases in sales and revenue.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] **Business decisions** - In reference to meeting goals, by having a thorough understanding of future industry demand, management and key board members can make strategic business decisions that encourage higher profitability and growth.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] These decisions are generally associated with the concepts of capacity, market targeting, raw material acquisition and understanding vendor contract direction.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] **Growth** - By having an accurate understanding of future forecasts, companies can gauge the need for expansion within a timeframe that allows them to do so cost effectively.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] **Human capital management** - If there is a rapid demand increase in an industry but a business does not have enough employees to satisfy the sales orders, consumer loyalty may be adversely affected as customers are forced to purchase from competitors.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] **Financial planning** - It is crucial to understand demand forecasts in order to efficiently budget for future operations in terms of factors such as cash flow, inventory accounting and general operational costs.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The use of an accurate demand forecasting model can result in significant decreases in operational costs for businesses, since less safety stock is required to be held.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] There are various statistical and econometric analyses used for forecasting demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The first step to forecast demand is to determine a set of objectives or information to derive different business strategies.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] These objectives are based on a set of hypotheses that usually come from a mixture of economic theory or previous empirical studies.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] For example, a manager may wish to find what the optimal price and production amount would be for a new product, based on how demand elasticity affected past company sales.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] There are many different econometric models which differ depending on the analysis that managers wish to perform.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The type of model that is chosen to forecast demand depends on many different aspects such as the type of data obtained or the number of observations, etc.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] In this stage it is important to define the type of variables that will be used to forecast demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Regression analysis is the main statistical method for forecasting.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] There are many different types of regression analysis, but fundamentally they provide an analysis of how one or multiple variables affect the dependent variable being measured.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] An example of a model for forecasting demand is M.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Roodman's (1986) demand forecasting regression model for measuring the seasonality affects on a data point being measured.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The model was based on a linear regression model, and is used to measure linear trends based on seasonal cycles and their affects on demand i.e. the seasonal demand for a product based on sales in summer and winter.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Where $Y_{i}$ is the dependent variable, $\beta _{0}$ is the intercept, $\beta _{1}$ is the slope coefficient, $X_{i}$ is the independent variable and e is the error term.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] $\lambda _{q}$ is defined as the set of all t - indices for quarter q.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Once the type of model is specified in stage 2, the data and the method of collecting data must be specified.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The model must be specified first in order to determine the variables which need to be collected.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Conversely, when deciding on the desired forecasting model, the available data or methods to collect data need to be considered in order to formulate the correct model.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Gathering Time series data and cross-sectional data are the different collection methods that may be used.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Time series data are based on historical observations taken sequentially in time.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] These observations are used to derive relevant statistics, characteristics, and insight from the data.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The data points that may be collected using time series data may be sales, prices, manufacturing costs, and their corresponding time intervals i.e., weekly, monthly, quarterly, annually, or any other regular interval.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Cross-sectional data refers to data collected on a single entity at different periods of time.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Cross-sectional data used in demand forecasting usually depicts a data point gathered from an individual, firm, industry, or area.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] For example, sales for Firm A during quarter 1.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] This type of data encapsulates a variety of data points which resulted in the final data point.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The subset of data points may not be observable or feasible to determine but can be a practical method for adding precision to the demand forecast model.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The source for the data can be found via the firm's records, commercial or private agencies, or official sources.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Once the model and data are obtained then the values can be computed to determine the effects the independent variables have on the dependent variable in focus.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The first step is to find the line that minimizes the sum of the squares of the difference between the observed values of the dependent variable and the fitted values from the line.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] $\beta _{0}$ and $\beta _{1}$ also need to be represented to find the intercept and slope of the line.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The method of determining $\beta _{0}$ and $\beta _{1}$ is to use partial differentiation with respect to both $\beta _{0}$ and $\beta _{1}$ by setting both expressions equal to zero and solving them simultaneously.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Calculating demand forecast accuracy is the process of determining the accuracy of forecasts made regarding customer demand for a product.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Understanding and predicting customer demand is vital to manufacturers and distributors to avoid stock-outs and to maintain adequate inventory levels.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] While forecasts are never perfect, they are necessary to prepare for actual demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] In order to maintain an optimized inventory and effective supply chain, accurate demand forecasts are imperative.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Forecast accuracy in the supply chain is typically measured using the Mean Absolute Percent Error or MAPE.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Statistically, MAPE is defined as the average of percentage errors.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Most practitioners, however, define and use the MAPE as the Mean Absolute Deviation divided by Average Sales, which is just a volume-weighted MAPE, also referred to as the MAD/Mean ratio.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] This is the same as dividing the sum of the absolute deviations by the total sales of all products.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] This calculation ${\frac {\sum {|A-F|}}{\sum {A}}}$ , where A is the actual value and F the forecast, is also known as WAPE, or the Weighted Absolute Percent Error.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Another interesting option is the weighted ${\text{MAPE}}={\frac {\sum (w\cdot |A-F|)}{\sum (w\cdot A)}}$ .
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The advantage of this measure is that can weight errors.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The only problem is that for seasonal products you will create an undefined result when sales = 0 and that is not symmetrical.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] This means that you can be much more inaccurate if sales are higher than if they are lower than the forecast.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] So sMAPE also known as symmetric Mean Absolute Percentage Error, is used to correct this.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Finally, for intermittent demand patterns, none of the above are particularly useful.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] In this situation, a business may consider MASE (Mean Absolute Scaled Error) as a key performance indicator to use.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] However, the use of this calculation is challenging as it is not as intuitive as the above-mentioned.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Another metric to consider, especially when there are intermittent or lumpy demand patterns at hand, is SPEC (Stock-keeping-oriented Prediction Error Costs).
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The idea behind this metric is to compare predicted demand and actual demand by computing theoretical incurred costs over the forecast horizon.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] It assumes, that predicted demand higher than actual demand results in stock-keeping costs, whereas predicted demand lower than actual demand results in opportunity costs.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] SPEC takes into account temporal shifts (prediction before or after actual demand) or cost-related aspects and allows comparisons between demand forecasts based on business aspects as well.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The forecast error needs to be calculated using actual sales as a base.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] There are several forms of forecast error calculation methods used, namely Mean Percent Error, Root Mean Squared Error, Tracking Signal and Forecast Bias.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] While statistical metrics such as MAPE and MSE measure the magnitude of error, they typically treat over-forecasts and under-forecasts symmetrically.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] However, in supply chain and financial contexts, the cost of error is often **asymmetric**.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The financial impact of carrying excess inventory (holding costs, obsolescence) rarely equals the financial impact of a stock-out (lost margin, expedited freight, loss of customer goodwill).
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Research into Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) environments has shown that standard forecasting modules often fail to account for these asymmetries, leading to sub-optimal inventory performance despite statistical accuracy.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The **Cost of Forecast Error (CFE)** is a metric designed to explicitly quantify this financial impact.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] By optimizing for minimum CFE rather than minimum statistical error, organizations can account for the "Symmetry Trap"—a situation where a statistically accurate forecast leads to sub-optimal financial outcomes.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Once the model has been determined, the model is used to test the theory or hypothesis stated in the first stage.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The results should describe what is trying to be achieved and determine if the theory or hypothesis is true or false.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] In relation to the example provided in the first stage, the model should show the relationship between demand elasticity of the market and the correlation it has to past company sales.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] This should enable managers to make an informed decisions regarding the optimal price and production levels for the new product.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] The final step is to then forecast demand based on the data set and model created.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] In order to forecast demand, estimations of a chosen variable are used to determine the effects it has on demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Regarding the estimation of the chosen variable, a regression model can be used or both qualitative and quantitative assessments can be implemented.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] In practice, demand forecasting methods are increasingly implemented through software platforms that use machine learning to analyze historical sales data and external factors.
[src:supply-chain-software/demand-forecasting] Examples include enterprise tools such as SAP Integrated Business Planning and AI-driven solutions like the Leafio AI, which provide predictive analytics for inventory and demand planning across multiple retail channels.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Military logistics is concerned with maintaining army supply lines with food, armaments, ammunition, and spare parts, apart from the transportation of troops themselves.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Civil logistics deals with acquiring, moving, and storing raw materials, semi-finished goods, and finished goods.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] For organisations that provide garbage collection, mail deliveries, public utilities, and after-sales services, logistical problems must be addressed.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Logistics deals with the movement of materials or products from one facility to another; it does not include material flow within production or assembly plants, such as production planning or single-machine scheduling.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Logistics accounts for a significant amount of the operational costs of an organisation or country.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Dedicated simulation software can model, analyse, visualise, and optimize logistic complexities.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Minimizing resource use is a common motivation in all logistics fields.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The term **logistics** is attested in English from 1846.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] It is from the French *logistique*, which was either coined or popularized by a Swiss military officer and writer, Antoine-Henri Jomini, who defined it in his *Summary of the Art of War* (*Précis de l'Art de la Guerre*).
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The term appears in the 1830 edition, then titled *Analytic Table* (*Tableau Analytique*), and Jomini explains that it is derived from French: **logis**, lit.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] 'lodgings' (cognate to English *lodge*), in the terms French: *maréchal des logis*, lit.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] 'marshall of lodgings' and French: *major-général des logis*, lit.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Chambray also notes that the term *logistique* was present in the *Dictionnaire de l'Académie française* as a synonym for algebra.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The French word: *logistique* is a homonym of the existing mathematical term, from Ancient Greek: λογῐστῐκός, romanized: *logistikós*, a traditional division of Greek mathematics; the mathematical term is presumably the origin of the term *logistic* in logistic growth and related terms.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Some sources give this instead as the source of *logistics*, either ignorant of Jomini's statement that it was derived from *logis*, or dubious and instead believing it was in fact of Greek origin, or influenced by the existing term of Greek origin.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The *Oxford English Dictionary* defines logistics as "the branch of military science relating to procuring, maintaining and transporting material, personnel and facilities".
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] However, the *New Oxford American Dictionary* defines logistics as "the detailed coordination of a complex operation involving many people, facilities, or supplies", and the Oxford Dictionary on-line defines it as "the detailed organization and implementation of a complex operation".
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] As such, logistics is commonly seen as a branch of engineering that creates "people systems" rather than "machine systems".
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] That being said, from a modeling perspective, there are similarities between operations management and logistics, and companies sometimes use hybrid professionals, with for example a "Director of Operations" or a "Logistics Officer" working on similar problems.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Furthermore, the term "supply chain management" originally referred to, among other issues, having an integrated vision of both production and logistics from the point of origin to the point of production.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Logistical activities can be divided into three main areas: order processing, inventory management, and freight transportation.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Modern freight transportation relies heavily on fleet management to improve efficiency and safety.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Traditionally, order processing was a time-consuming activity, but with new technologies such as bar code scanning and computers, the availability of stocks can be checked in real time.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The purpose of having an inventory is to reduce the overall logistical cost while improving service to customers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Having a stockpile of finished goods beforehand can reduce the frequency of transportation and cope with the randomness of customer demands.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] However, maintaining an inventory requires capital investment and maintaining a warehouse.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Freight transportation is a central part of logistics and allows access to broad markets.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Transportation policies and warehouse management are closely intertwined.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The rise of e-commerce has led to the development of "e-logistics".
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Compared to traditional logistics, e-logistics handles parcels valued at less than a hundred US dollars and delivers them to customers scattered across various destinations worldwide.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In e-logistics, customer demand tends to come in waves, unlike in traditional logistics, where demand is more consistent.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In addition, the term *production logistics* describes logistic processes within a value-adding system (e.g., a factory or a mine).
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Production logistics aims to ensure that each machine and workstation receives the right product in the correct quantity and quality at the right time.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The concern is with production, testing, transportation, storage, and supply.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Production logistics can operate in existing as well as new plants.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Since manufacturing in an existing plant is a constantly changing process, machines are exchanged and new ones added, which allows for improving the production logistics system accordingly.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Production logistics provides the means to achieve customer response and capital efficiency.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Track and trace solutions, which provide visibility of products through the production line, are an important part of modern production logistics, especially in the automotive and medical industries.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The term *construction logistics* has also been employed by civilizations for thousands of years.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Now, construction logistics is an important part of the sector.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In recent years, it has emerged as a distinct field of study within supply chain management and logistics.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Modern construction logistics uses automatic vehicle location (AVL) to manage the movement of heavy equipment and materials.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In military science, maintaining one's supply lines while disrupting those of the enemy is a crucial element of military strategy, since an armed force without resources and transportation is defenseless.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The defeat of the British in the American War of Independence and the defeat of the Axis in the African theater of World War II are attributed by some scholars to logistical failures.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Militaries have a significant need for logistics solutions and so have developed advanced implementations.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In military logistics, Logistics Officers manage how and when to move resources to the places they are needed.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Supply chain management in military logistics often deals with a number of variables in predicting cost, deterioration, consumption, and future demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The United States Armed Forces' categorical supply classification was developed in such a way that categories of supply with similar consumption variables are grouped together for planning purposes.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] For instance, peacetime consumption of ammunition and fuel will be considerably lower than wartime consumption of these items, whereas other classes of supply such as subsistence and clothing have a relatively consistent consumption rate regardless of war or peace.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Some classes of supply have a linear demand relationship: as more troops are added, more supply items are needed; or as more equipment is used, more fuel and ammunition are consumed.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Other classes of supply must consider a third variable besides usage and quantity: time.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] As equipment ages, more and more repair parts are needed over time, even when usage and quantity stay consistent.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] By recording and analyzing these trends over time and applying them to future scenarios, the US Armed Forces can accurately supply troops with the items necessary at the precise moment they are needed.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] History has shown that good logistical planning creates a lean and efficient fighting force.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The lack thereof can lead to a clunky, slow, and ill-equipped force with too much or too little supply.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] One definition of business logistics speaks of "having the right item in the right quantity at the right time at the right place for the right price in the right condition to the right customer".
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Business logistics incorporates all industry sectors and aims to manage the fruition of project life cycles, supply chains, and resultant efficiencies.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The term *business logistics* has evolved since the 1960s due to the increasing complexity of supplying businesses with materials and shipping out products in an increasingly globalized supply chain, leading to a call for professionals called supply chain logisticians.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In business, logistics may have either an internal focus (inbound logistics) or an external focus (outbound logistics), covering the flow and storage of materials from point of origin to point of consumption, a key factor in supply-chain management.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The main functions of a qualified logistician include inventory management, purchasing, transportation, warehousing, consultation, and the organizing and planning of these activities.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Logisticians combine professional knowledge of each of these functions to coordinate resources in an organization.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] There are two fundamentally different forms of logistics: one optimizes a steady flow of material through a network of transport links and storage nodes, while the other coordinates a sequence of resources to carry out some project, such as restructuring a warehouse.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A **journey planner** or **route optimization** software is often used to solve the complex logistical problem of determining the most efficient delivery paths for a fleet of vehicles.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] These systems, which are a key component of an **intelligent transportation system**, analyze factors like traffic, delivery windows, and vehicle capacity to create optimized routes that reduce fuel consumption and improve on-time performance.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A distribution network would require several intermediaries to bring consumer or industrial goods from manufacturers to a user.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Intermediaries would markup the costs of the products during distribution, but benefit users by providing lower transportation costs than the manufacturers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The number of intermediaries required for the distribution network depends upon the types of goods being distributed.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] For example, consumer goods such as cosmetics and handicrafts may not require any intermediaries as they can be sold door-to-door or can be obtained from local flea markets.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] For industrial goods such as raw materials and equipment, intermediaries are not needed because manufacturers can sell a large number of goods to a user.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Generally, there are three types of intermediaries, namely: agent/broker, wholesaler, and retailer.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A logistic family is a set of products that share a common characteristic: weight and volumetric characteristics, physical storing needs (temperature, radiation, etc.), handling needs, order frequency, package size, etc.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Other metrics may present themselves in both physical or monetary form, such as the standard inventory turnover.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Unit loads are combinations of individual items which are moved by handling systems, usually employing a pallet of normed dimensions.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Handling systems include: trans-pallet handlers, counterweight handler, retractable mast handler, bilateral handlers, trilateral handlers, AGV and other handlers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Storage systems include: pile stocking, cell racks (either static or movable), cantilever racks and gravity racks.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Picking can be both manual or automated.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Manual picking can be both man-to-goods, i.e. operator using a cart or conveyor belt, or goods-to-man, i.e. the operator benefiting from the presence of a mini-load ASRS, vertical or horizontal carousel or from an Automatic Vertical Storage System (AVSS).
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Automatic picking is done either with dispensers or depalletizing robots.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Sorting can be done manually through carts or conveyor belts, or automatically through sorters.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Consolidating small shipments into large shipments can help to save transportation costs.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] There are three methods to do this: facility consolidation, multi-stop consolidation, and temporal consolidation.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Facility consolidation uses the economics of scale by transporting small shipments over short distances and large shipments over long distances.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Multi-stop consolidation makes multiple stops to consolidate small shipments in the case of less-than-truckload shipping.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Temporal consolidation adjusts the shipping schedules forwards or backward so as to make a single large shipment rather than several small shipments over time.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Cargo can be consolidated into pallets or containers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] There are five basic modes of transport, namely, ship, rail, truck, air, and pipeline operated by different carriers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] These shipping methods can be combined in various ways such as intermodal transport (no handling), multimodal transport, and combined transport (minimal road transport).
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A shipper chooses a carrier by taking into account the total cost of shipment and transit time.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Air is the most expensive type of transport, followed by truck, rail, pipeline, and ship.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Cargo can be organized in different shipment categories.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Unit loads are usually assembled into higher standardized units such as: ISO containers, swap bodies or semi-trailers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Especially for very long distances, product transportation will likely benefit from using different transportation means: When moving cargo, typical constraints are maximum weight and volume.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Operators involved in transportation include: all train, road vehicles, boats, airplanes companies, couriers, freight forwarders and multi-modal transport operators.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Merchandise being transported internationally is usually subject to the Incoterms standards issued by the International Chamber of Commerce.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In the logistics business, a logistical system is designed at a minimum cost based on the expected customer service level.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] As the service improves, the number of sales also increased.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] As service is further improved, more sales are captured from competing providers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Further increase in customer service levels after these only increases sales marginally.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Similarly to production systems, logistic systems need to be properly configured and managed.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Actually a number of methodologies have been directly borrowed from operations management such as using economic order quantity models for managing inventory in the nodes of the network.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Distribution resource planning (DRP) is similar to MRP, except that it does not concern activities inside the nodes of the network but planning distribution when moving goods through the links of the network.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Traditionally in logistics, configuration may be at the level of the warehouse (node) or at level of the distribution system (network).
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Some important constraints have to be satisfied: fork and load beams resistance to bending and proper placement of sprinklers.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Configuration at the level of the distribution system concerns primarily the problem of location of the nodes in geographic space and distribution of capacity among the nodes.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The first may be referred to as facility location (with the special case of site selection) while the latter to as capacity allocation.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The problem of outsourcing typically arises at this level: the nodes of a supply chain are very rarely owned by a single enterprise.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Transportation from producer to the second level is called primary transportation, from the second level to a consumer is called secondary transportation.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Once a logistic system is configured, management, meaning tactical decisions, takes place, once again, at the level of the warehouse and of the distribution network.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Decisions have to be made under a set of constraints: internal, such as using the available infrastructure, or external, such as complying with the given product shelf lifes and expiration dates.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] At the warehouse level, the logistician must decide how to distribute merchandise over the racks.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Three basic situations are traditionally considered: shared storage, dedicated storage (rack space reserved for specific merchandise) and class-based storage (class meaning merchandise organized in different areas according to their access index).
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Picking efficiency varies greatly depending on the situation.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] For a man to goods situation, a distinction is carried out between high-level picking (vertical component significant) and low-level picking (vertical component insignificant).
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] At the level of the distribution network, tactical decisions involve mainly inventory control and delivery path optimization.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Note that the logistician may be required to manage the reverse flow along with the forward flow.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Warehouse management systems (WMS) can differ significantly from warehouse control systems (WCS), although there is some overlap in functionality.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A WMS plans a weekly activity forecast based on such factors as statistics and trends, whereas a WCS acts like a floor supervisor, working in real-time to get the job done by the most effective means.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] For example, a WMS can tell the system that it is going to need five of stock-keeping unit (SKU) A and five of SKU B hours in advance, but by the time it acts, other considerations may have come into play or there could be a logjam on a conveyor.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A WCS can prevent that problem by working in real-time and adapting to the situation by making a last-minute decision based on current activity and operational status.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Working synergistically, WMS and WCS can resolve these issues and maximize efficiency for companies that rely on the effective operation of their warehouse or distribution center.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Third-party logistics (3PL) involves using external organizations to execute logistics activities that have traditionally been performed within an organization itself.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] According to this definition, third-party logistics includes any form of outsourcing of logistics activities previously performed in house.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] For example, if a company with its own warehousing facilities decides to employ external transportation, this would be an example of third-party logistics.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Logistics is an emerging business area in many countries.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] External 3PL providers have evolved from merely providing logistics capabilities to becoming real orchestrators of supply chains that create and sustain a competitive advantage, thus bringing about new levels of logistics outsourcing.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Whereas a third-party logistics (3PL) service provider targets a single function, a 4PL targets management of the entire process.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Some have described a 4PL as a general contractor that manages other 3PLs, truckers, forwarders, custom house agents, and others, essentially taking responsibility of a complete process for the customer.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Horizontal business alliances often occur between logistics service providers, i.e., the cooperation between two or more logistics companies that are potentially competing.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In a horizontal alliance, these partners can benefit twofold.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] On one hand, they can "access tangible resources which are directly exploitable".
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In this example extending common transportation networks, their warehouse infrastructure and the ability to provide more complex service packages can be achieved by combining resources.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] On the other hand, partners can "access intangible resources, which are not directly exploitable".
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] This typically includes know-how and information and, in turn, innovation.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] This typically refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Industrial machinery can typically identify products through either barcode or RFID technologies.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Information in traditional bar codes is stored as a sequence of black and white bars varying in width, which when read by laser is translated into a digital sequence, which according to fixed rules can be converted into a decimal number or other data.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Sometimes information in a bar code can be transmitted through radio frequency, more typically radio transmission is used in RFID tags.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] An RFID tag is a card containing a memory chip and an antenna that transmits signals to a reader.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] RFID may be found on merchandise, animals, vehicles, and people as well.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A logistician is a professional logistics practitioner.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Professional logisticians are often certified by professional associations.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] One can either work in a pure logistics company, such as a shipping line, airport, or freight forwarder, or within the logistics department of a company.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] However, as mentioned above, logistics is a broad field, encompassing procurement, production, distribution, and disposal activities.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Hence, career perspectives are broad as well.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A new trend in the industry is the 4PL, or fourth-party logistics, firms, consulting companies offering logistics services.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] Some universities and academic institutions train students as logisticians, offering undergraduate and postgraduate programs.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] A university with a primary focus on logistics is Kühne Logistics University in Hamburg, Germany.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] It is non-profit and supported by Kühne-Foundation of the logistics entrepreneur Klaus Michael Kühne.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport (CILT), established in the United Kingdom in 1919, received a Royal Charter in 1926.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The Chartered Institute is one of the professional bodies or institutions for the logistics and transport sectors that offer professional qualifications or degrees in logistics management.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] CILT programs can be studied at centers around the UK, some of which also offer distance learning options.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The institute also has overseas branches, namely the Chartered Institute of Logistics & Transport Australia (CILTA) in Australia, and the Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport in Hong Kong (CILTHK) in Hong Kong.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] In the UK, logistics management programs are conducted by many universities and professional bodies such as CILT.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] These programs are generally offered at the postgraduate level.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The Global Institute of Logistics, established in New York in 2003, is a think tank for the profession and is primarily concerned with intercontinental maritime logistics.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] It is particularly concerned with container logistics and the role of the seaport authority in the maritime logistics chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The International Association of Public Health Logisticians (IAPHL) is a professional network that promotes the professional development of supply chain managers and others working in the field of public health logistics and commodity security, with particular focus on developing countries.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] The association supports logisticians worldwide by providing a community of practice, where members can network, exchange ideas, and improve their professional skills.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] There are many museums in the world which cover various aspects of practical logistics.
[src:supply-chain-software/logistics] These include museums of transportation, customs, packing, and industry-based logistics.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Procurement as an organizational process is intended to ensure that the buyer receives goods, services, or works at the best possible price when aspects such as quality, quantity, time, and location are compared.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Corporations and public bodies often define processes intended to promote fair and open competition for their business while minimizing risks such as exposure to fraud and collusion.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In practice, the procurement process is commonly organized into seven steps that provide structure and consistency across purchasing activities.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Almost all purchasing decisions include factors such as delivery and handling, marginal benefit, and fluctuations in the prices of goods.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Organisations that have adopted a corporate social responsibility perspective are also likely to require their purchasing activity to take wider societal and ethical considerations into account.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] On the other hand, the introduction of external regulations concerning accounting practices can affect ongoing buyer-supplier relations in unforeseen ways.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The Institute for Supply Management (ISM) defines procurement as an organizational function that includes specification development, value analysis, supplier market research, negotiation, buying activities, contract administration, inventory control, traffic, receiving and stores.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] A company's procurement function, specifically its spending on suppliers, typically accounts for more than half of the company's total budget.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Purchasing is a subset of procurement that specifically deals with the ordering and payment of goods and services.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Organizational procurement is also referred to as "organizational buying" or "institutional buying," for example, in studies of the buying behavior of staff involved in purchasing decision-making.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Procurement activities are also often divided into two distinct categories, direct and indirect spend.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Direct spend refers to the production-related procurement that encompasses all items that are part of finished products, such as raw materials, components and parts.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Direct procurement, which is the focus in supply chain management, directly affects the production process of manufacturing firms.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In contrast, indirect procurement concerns non-production-related acquisition: a wide variety of goods and services, from standardized items like office supplies and safety equipment to complex and costly products and services like heavy equipment, consulting services, and outsourcing services.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] A 2011 report found that the average procurement department manages 60.6% of total enterprise spend.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] This measure, commonly called "spend under management" or "managed spend", refers to the percentage of total enterprise spend (which includes all direct and indirect spend) that a procurement organization manages or influences.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Alternatively, the term may refer to the percentage of addressable spend which is influenced by procurement, "addressable spend" being the expenditure which could potentially be influenced.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The average procurement department also achieved an annual saving of 6.7% in the last reporting cycle, sourced 52.6% of its addressable spend, and has a contract compliance rate of 62.6%.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] A more restrictive definition of "spend under management" includes only expenditure that makes use of preferred supplier contracts and negotiated payment rates and terms.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The Romans developed a military logistics system of supply depots that were located throughout their empire.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] These depots were stocked with food, weapons, and other supplies that could be quickly distributed to troops in the field.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] This system helped to ensure that the Roman army was always well-supplied, even when it was fighting far from home.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Procurement is one component of the broader concept of sourcing and acquisition.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Typically procurement is viewed as more tactical in nature (the process of physically buying a product or service) and sourcing and acquisition are viewed as more strategic and encompassing.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The term procurement is used to reflect the entire purchasing process or cycle, and not just the tactical components.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Procurement software (often labeled as e-procurement software) manages purchasing processes electronically.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Some aspects of a procurement process may need to be initiated ahead of the majority of the project, for example where there are extensive lead times.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Such cases may be referred to as "advance procurement".
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] At this point the cycle would recommence.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Bunn notes that search activities are a central preliminary action to be undertaken before buying decisions can be made.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Procurement decisions fall along a continuum from simple buying transactions to more complex buyer-supplier collaborations, and the buying behaviour of staff involved in purchasing decision-making has been widely studied.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] There is a consensus among scholars and marketing managers that buyers utilise various decision processes as appropriate to each buying situation, and some purchasing decisions are especially complex.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Some writers treat purchasing decisions as examples of rational behaviour made in the context of a business aim such as profit maximisation and make the assumption that decision-makers have access to the information they need for their decision.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Feldman and Cordozo questioned this approach in a 1969 article, suggesting that industrial buyer decision-making had similarities with consumer buying behaviour.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Wilson suggested in a 1971 article that an individual buyer's personality should be considered in understanding buyers' decision processes.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Wilson found that there was some correlation between personality traits and decision-making styles among the Canadian buyers who participated in his research study.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Jagdish Sheth published *A Model of Industrial Buyer Behavior* in 1973, which drew from a large volume of empirical study of buyer behaviour and emphasised how the "psychological world of the decision-makers" impacted on the processes and outcomes of purchasing decision-making.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] There are wide variations in the involvement of procurement staff in purchasing decisions across types of organisation and across varying purchasing situations.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Some purchasing decisions are made by individuals or groups of individuals referred to as a "buying center" or "decision-making unit", where procurement personnel may in some cases be central, in other cases peripheral, to the purchasing decision.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] From a marketing perspective, buying center research has looked at which individuals and organisational divisions become part of the decision-making group, how they interact, and the internal and external factors which influence purchasing outcomes.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Government procurement or public procurement is the purchase of goods, works (construction), or services by the state, such as by a government agency or a state-owned enterprise.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In 2019, public procurement accounted for approximately 12% of GDP in OECD countries.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In 2021, the World Bank Group estimated that public procurement made up about 15% of global GDP.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Therefore, government procurement accounts for a substantial part of the global economy.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Electronic procurement is the purchasing of goods by businesses through the internet or other networked computer connection.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Electronic data interchange (EDI) was a forerunner to electronic procurement, this consisted of standardized transmission of data such as inventories and good required electronically.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Schoenherr argues that EDI developed from standardized manifests for deliveries to Berlin during the Berlin Airlift which were applied by DuPont in the 1960s and argues that Material requirements planning and Enterprise resource planning were both forerunners to electronic procurement.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] E-procurement involves various components like e-sourcing, e-tendering, e-auctions.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Joint procurement takes place when two or more organisations share purchasing activities, and therefore has a more specifically buyer-side focus than many examples of collaborative buyer-seller relationships.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Joint or collaborative procurement is a common practice within public sector procurement.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] There are central purchasing bodies in many countries which coordinate joint purchasing activities for public sector organisations.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] A report commissioned by the European Parliament's Committee on the Internal Market and Consumer Protection (IMCO) has recommended that EU Member States "should consider creating Central Purchasing Bodies (CPBs)" in order to secure "coherent and coordinated procurement".
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] On a trans-national scale, Guyana, Barbados and Rwanda announced "a programme of mutual support for the local manufacturing of vaccines and medicines" in July 2023 for which a "pooled procurement mechanism" would be required.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] CIPS has in the past also offered an alternative listing of the five rights as "buy[ing] goods or services of the right quality, in the right quantity, from the right source, at the right time and at the right price.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] 'Right source' is added as a sixth right in CIPS' 2018 publication, *Contract Administration*.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Delivery on savings goals is an important part of the procurement function, but this objective is generally seen as value generation rather than cost reduction.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] CIPS also notes that securing savings is "one measure of purchasing performance", but argues that savings should only be used as a measure of performance where they are "a reflection of the [organisation]'s ... expectations of the purchasing and supply management function".
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] CIPS distinguishes between "savings", which can reduce budgets, and "cost avoidance", which "attempts to thwart price increases and to keep within budget".
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Findings in 2020 suggested that "top quartile procurement performers have ROSMA scores two to three times higher than those in the middle two quartiles".
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Spend under management also contributes to an additional measure of procurement performance or procurement efficiency: procurement operating expense as a percentage of managed spend.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The intensity of competition during procurement can be measured by the number of bids.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Division of the procurement into smaller lots and the possibility of negotiation can increase competition.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Competition law can prevent bid rigging.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Personnel who undertake procurement on behalf of an organization may be referred to as procurement officers, professionals or specialists, buyers or supply managers.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The US Federal Acquisition Regulation refers to Contracting Officers.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Staff in managerial positions may be referred to as Purchasing Managers or Procurement Managers.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The ISM refers to "the supply profession".
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Bartolini and Dwyer note that allocating the benefits of savings across an organization, e.g. by negotiating departmental budget reductions, should not be treated as a procurement role: this is a financial role.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Category management represents a system of organising the roles of staff within a procurement team "in such a way as to focus ... on the [external] supply markets of an organisation", rather than being organised according to the organisation's internal departmental structure.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Specialist procurement roles include construction buyers and travel buyers.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Part of the work of a corporate travel buyer is the formulation and implementation of a corporate travel policy.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In many larger organizations the procurement and supply function is led by a board-level or other senior position such as a Director of Supply Chain or a chief procurement officer (CPO).
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In other cases, procurement is overseen by the chief financial officer (CFO) or Director of Finance, or the growing need for liaison between the CFO and the procurement function has been recognised.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] A 2006 report by the National Audit Office in the UK commented that in the further education sector, where procurement practice was not well developed and college organisations were relatively small, oversight of procurement by the Director of Finance was a typical arrangement.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] A commercial agent may both purchase and sell on behalf of a third party.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] US Bureau of Labor Statistics research found that there were 526,200 purchasing manager, buyer and purchasing agent positions in the United States in 2019.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Various writers have noted that businesses may reduce the numbers of purchasing staff during a recession along with staff in other business areas, despite a tendency to become more dependent on bought-in goods and services as operations contract.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] For example, US business executive Steve Collins observed that in one major company the purchasing staffbase "was downsized some 30% during the [2010] recession, 'but the expectations for the remaining employees remained unchanged ...
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The additional workload placed on the remaining employees following the downsizing created a much more challenging environment'".
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In 2021 the Australasian Procurement and Construction Council (APCC) put forward an appeal asking everyone working in the procurement profession in Australia to include the term in their occupational title when completing their August 2021 census return.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Research undertaken in 2020 highlighted the importance of social or "soft" skills within the skill sets of professional procurement staff.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Some writers have observed that there are limited opportunities for women to enter procurement because of stereotypes that view some roles as inappropriate for women.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] The effect of this growing involvement of women in procurement was recognised in the form of "more creativity and innovation", acknowledged by 76% of the CPO's surveyed.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] A contractual obligation to procure refers to an absolute obligation to ensure that the action is done or the condition is met.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] For example, when a party to a construction contract is obligated to apply for the permits required to commence work, that party is obligated to apply for them.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Where such a contract is silent as to which party is responsible to seek permits, but only one party is capable of doing so, it is implicit within the contract that the capable party will obtain permits within a reasonable time frame so as to allow the work to proceed.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] In this case, the obligation to "procure the payment" of the loan amounted to a guarantee of that loan.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Various commentators have made projections regarding the future of procurement.
[src:supply-chain-software/procurement] Charlotte Payne, general manager of CIPS in Australia and New Zealand, suggests that "procurement's role in sustainability is going to be massive", while a CIPS general overview anticipates that "there is little chance that procurement and supply will enter a period of calm any time soon".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In commerce, **supply chain management** (**SCM**) deals with a system of procurement (purchasing raw materials/components), operations management, logistics and marketing channels, through which raw materials can be developed into finished products and delivered to their end customers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This can include the movement and storage of raw materials, work-in-process inventory, finished goods, and end-to-end order fulfilment from the point of origin to the point of consumption.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Interconnected, interrelated or interlinked networks, channels and node businesses combine in the provision of products and services required by end customers in a supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM is the broad range of activities required to plan, control and execute a product's flow from materials to production to distribution in the most economical way possible.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM encompasses the integrated planning and execution of processes required to optimize the flow of materials, information and capital in functions that broadly include demand planning, sourcing, production, inventory management and logistics—or storage and transportation.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management strives for an integrated, multidisciplinary, multi-method approach.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Research in supply chain management focuses on topics such as resilience, sustainability, and risk management, among others.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Some suggest that the "people dimension" of SCM, ethical issues, internal integration, transparency/visibility, and human capital or talent management are topics that have been underrepresented on the research agenda.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management, techniques with the aim of coordinating all parts of SC, from supplying raw materials to delivering and/or resumption of products, tries to minimize total costs with respect to existing conflicts among the chain partners.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] An example of these conflicts is the interrelation between the sale department desiring to have higher inventory levels to fulfill demands and the warehouse for which lower inventories are desired to reduce holding costs.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In 1982, Keith Oliver, a consultant at Booz Allen Hamilton, introduced the term "supply chain management" to the public domain in an interview for the Financial Times.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In the mid-1990s, the term "supply chain management" gained popularity when a flurry of articles and books came out on the subject.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chains were originally defined as encompassing all activities associated with the flow and transformation of goods from raw materials through to the end user or final consumer, as well as the associated information flows.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Mentzer *et al.* consider it worthy of note that the final consumer was included within these early definitions.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management was then further defined as the integration of supply chain activities through improved supply chain relationships to achieve a competitive advantage.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In the late 1990s, "supply chain management" (SCM) rose to prominence, and operations managers began to use it in their titles with increasing regularity.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] A supply chain, as opposed to supply chain management, is a set of firms who move materials "forward", or a set of organizations, directly linked by one or more upstream and downstream flows of products, services, finances, or information from a source to a customer.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is the management of such a chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Mentzer *et al.* make a further distinction between "supply chain management" and a "supply chain orientation".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The latter term involves a recognition that a business strategy cannot be fulfilled without managing the activities of suppliers and customers upstream and downstream, whereas the former term is used for "the actual implementation of this orientation".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management software includes tools or modules used to execute supply chain transactions, manage supplier relationships, and control associated business processes.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The overall goal of the software is to improve supply chain performance by monitoring a company's supply chain network from end-to-end (suppliers, transporters, returns, warehouses, retailers, manufacturers, and customers).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In some cases, a supply chain includes the collection of goods after consumer use for recycling or the reverse logistics processes for returning faulty or unwanted products back to producers up the value chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is a cross-functional approach that includes managing the movement of raw materials into an organization, certain aspects of the internal processing of materials into finished goods, and the movement of finished goods out of the organization and toward the end consumer.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] As organizations strive to focus on core competencies and become more flexible, they reduce ownership of raw materials sources and distribution channels.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] These functions are increasingly being outsourced to other firms that can perform the activities better or more cost effectively.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The effect is to increase the number of organizations involved in satisfying customer demand, while reducing managerial control of daily logistics operations.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Less control and more supply chain partners lead to the creation of the concept of supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is concerned with improving trust and collaboration among supply chain partners, thus improving inventory visibility and the velocity of inventory movement.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Organizations increasingly find that they must rely on effective supply chains, or networks, to compete in the global market and networked economy.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In Peter Drucker's (1998) new management paradigms, this concept of business relationships extends beyond traditional enterprise boundaries and seeks to organize entire business processes throughout a value chain of multiple companies.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In recent decades, globalization, outsourcing, and information technology have enabled many organizations, such as Dell and Hewlett-Packard, to successfully operate collaborative supply networks in which each specialized business partner focuses on only a few key strategic activities.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This inter-organizational supply network can be acknowledged as a new form of organization.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] However, with the complicated interactions among the players, the network structure fits neither "market" nor "hierarchy" categories.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] It is not clear what kind of performance impacts different supply-network structures could have on firms, and little is known about the coordination conditions and trade-offs that may exist among the players.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] From a systems perspective, a complex network structure can be decomposed into individual component firms.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Traditionally, companies in a supply network concentrate on the inputs and outputs of the processes, with little concern for the internal management working of other individual players.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Therefore, the choice of an internal management control structure is known to impact local firm performance.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In the 21st century, changes in the business environment have contributed to the development of supply chain networks.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] First, as an outcome of globalization and the proliferation of multinational companies, joint ventures, strategic alliances, and business partnerships, significant success factors were identified, complementing the earlier "just-in-time", lean manufacturing, and agile manufacturing practices.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Second, technological changes, particularly the dramatic fall in communication costs (a significant component of transaction costs), have led to changes in coordination among the members of the supply chain network.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Many researchers have recognized supply network structures as a new organizational form, using terms such as "Keiretsu", "Extended Enterprise", "virtual supply chain", "Global Production Network", and "Next Generation Manufacturing System".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In general, such a structure can be defined as "a group of semi-independent organizations, each with their capabilities, which collaborate in ever-changing constellations to serve one or more markets in order to achieve some business goal specific to that collaboration".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain management is also important for organizational learning.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Firms with geographically more extensive supply chains connecting diverse trading cliques tend to become more innovative and productive.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The security-management system for supply chains is described in ISO/IEC 28000 and ISO/IEC 28001 and related standards published jointly by the ISO and the IEC.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply Chain Management draws heavily from the areas of operations management, logistics, procurement, and information technology, and strives for an integrated approach.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The importance of supply chain management proved crucial in the 2019-2020 fight against the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic that swept across the world.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] During the pandemic period, governments in countries which had in place effective domestic supply chain management had enough medical supplies to support their needs and enough to donate their surplus to front-line health workers in other jurisdictions.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The devastating COVID-19 crisis in US has turned many sectors of the local economy upside down, including the country's storied logistics industry.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Some organizations were able to quickly develop foreign supply chains in order to import much needed medical supplies.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Cross-border supply chains can increase political risk.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] An important element of SCM is supply chain resilience, defined as "the capacity of a supply chain to persist, adapt, or transform in the face of change".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] For a long time, the interpretation of resilience in the sense of engineering resilience (= robustness) prevailed in supply chain management, leading to the notion of *persistence*.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] A popular implementation of this idea is given by measuring the *time-to-survive* and the *time-to-recover* of the supply chain, allowing to identify weak points in the system.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The APICS Certified Supply Chain Professional (CSCP) program emphasizes the importance of managing risks and enhancing resilience.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] According to APICS, in order to manage global interruptions and preserve operational continuity, a robust supply chain is vital.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] More recently, the interpretations of resilience in the sense of ecological resilience and social–ecological resilience have led to the notions of *adaptation* and *transformation*, respectively.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In a simple form, ecological resilience represents the capacity of a system to absorb disturbances and survive despite these changes.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The ecological resilience is different from conditions far from equilibrium steady states, where disturbances and instabilities may shift a system into a different regime of behavior or stability domain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This leads to a panarchical interpretation of a supply chain, embedding it into a system of systems, allowing to analyze the interactions of the supply chain with systems that operate at other levels (e.g. society, political economy, planet Earth).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] For example, these three components of resilience can be discussed for the 2021 Suez Canal obstruction, when a ship blocked the canal for several days.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Persistence means to "bounce back"; in our example it is about removing the ship as quickly as possible to allow "normal" operations.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Adaptation means to accept that the system has reached a "new normal" state and to act accordingly; here, this can be implemented by redirecting ships around the African cape or use alternative modes of transport.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Finally, transformation means to question the assumptions of globalization, outsourcing and linear supply chains and to envision alternatives; in this example this could lead to local and circular supply chains that do not need global transportation routes any longer.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Public policy can increase the resilience of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Six major movements can be observed in the evolution of supply chain management studies: creation, integration, globalization, specialization phases one and two, and SCM 2.0.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The term "supply chain management" was first coined by Keith Oliver in 1982.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] However, the concept of a supply chain in management was of great importance long before, in the early 20th century, especially with the creation of the assembly line.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The characteristics of this era of supply chain management include the need for large-scale changes, re-engineering, downsizing driven by cost reduction programs, and widespread attention to Japanese management practices.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] However, the term became widely adopted after the publication of the seminal book *Introduction to Supply Chain Management* in 1999 by Robert B.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Nichols, Jr., which published over 25,000 copies and was translated into Japanese, Korean, Chinese, and Russian.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This era of supply chain management studies was highlighted with the development of electronic data interchange (EDI) systems in the 1960s and developed through the 1990s by the introduction of enterprise resource planning (ERP) systems.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This era has continued to develop into the 21st century with the expansion of Internet-based collaborative systems.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This era of supply chain evolution is characterized by both increasing value-added and reducing costs through integration.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] A supply chain can be classified as a stage 1, 2, or 3 network.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In stage 1–type supply chain, systems such as production, storage, distribution, and material control are not linked and are independent of each other.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In a stage 2 supply chain, these are integrated under one plan, and enterprise resource planning (ERP) is enabled.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] A stage 3 supply chain is one that achieves vertical integration with upstream suppliers and downstream customers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] An example of this kind of supply chain is Tesco.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] It is the third movement of supply chain management development, the globalization era, can be characterized by the attention given to global systems of supplier relationships and the expansion of supply chains beyond national boundaries and into other continents.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Although the use of global sources in organizations' supply chains can be traced back several decades (e.g., in the oil industry), it was not until the late 1980s that a considerable number of organizations started to integrate global sources into their core business.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This era is characterized by the globalization of supply chain management in organizations with the goal of increasing their competitive advantage, adding value, and reducing costs through global sourcing.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In the 1990s, companies began to focus on "core competencies" and specialization.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] They abandoned vertical integration, sold off non-core operations, and outsourced those functions to other companies.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This changed management requirements, as the supply chain extended beyond the company walls and management was distributed across specialized supply chain partnerships.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This transition also refocused the fundamental perspectives of each organization.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) became brand owners that required visibility deep into their supply base.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] They had to control the entire supply chain from above, instead of from within.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Contract manufacturers had to manage bills of material with different part-numbering schemes from multiple OEMs and support customer requests for work-in-process visibility and vendor-managed inventory (VMI).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The specialization model creates manufacturing and distribution networks composed of several individual supply chains specific to producers, suppliers, and customers that work together to design, manufacture, distribute, market, sell, and service a product.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This set of partners may change according to a given market, region, or channel, resulting in a proliferation of trading partner environments, each with its own unique characteristics and demands.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Market forces sometimes demand rapid changes from suppliers, logistics providers, locations, or customers in their role as components of supply chain networks.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Outsourced technology hosting for supply chain solutions debuted in the late 1990s and has taken root primarily in transportation and collaboration categories.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This has progressed from the application service provider (ASP) model from roughly 1998 through 2003 to the on-demand model from approximately 2003 through 2006, to the software as a service (SaaS) model currently in focus today.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The term SCM 2.0 has been coined to describe both changes within supply chains themselves as well as the evolution of processes, methods, and tools to manage them in a new era of globalization and specialization.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] One element of this is the growing popularity of supply chain collaboration platforms that connect multiple buyers and suppliers with financial institutions, enabling them to conduct automated supply chain finance transactions.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Web 2.0 is a trend in the use of the World Wide Web that is meant to increase creativity, information sharing, and collaboration among users.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] At its core, the common attribute of Web 2.0 is to help navigate the vast information available on the Web in order to find what is being bought.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM 2.0 replicates this notion in supply chain operations.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Increasing volatility has characterized supply chains since about 2000.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] SCM components are the third element of the four-square circulation framework.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The level of integration and management of a business process link is a function of the number and level of components added to the link.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Consequently, adding more management components or increasing the level of each component can increase the level of integration of the business process link.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Literature on business process reengineering, buyer-supplier relationships, and SCM suggests various possible components that should receive managerial attention when managing supply relationships.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Bowersox and Closs (1996) state that the emphasis on cooperation represents the synergism leading to the highest level of joint achievement.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] A primary-level channel participant is a business that is willing to participate in responsibility for inventory ownership or assume other financial risks, thus including primary level components.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] A secondary-level participant (specialized) is a business that participates in channel relationships by performing essential services for primary participants, including secondary level components, which support primary participants.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Third-level channel participants and components that support primary-level channel participants and are the fundamental branches of secondary-level components may also be included.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Andrew Cox, Joe Sanderson and Glyn Watson argue that the power resources of buyers and suppliers should be analyzed in order to understand how a supply chain relationship operates.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In some cases, a purchasing firm may exercise more power over its suppliers, in other cases, suppliers may have more power; yet again there will be cases where buyers and suppliers may be interdependent or may have no real power over each other.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Cox, Sanderson and Watson have written extensively on the operation of power regimes within a supply chain context; they have described their work for themselves as "a new perspective on managing in supply chains and networks".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Other studies of power in supply chain relationships have looked at drivers impacting on the potential integration of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Benton in 1998 looked at whether potential asymmetries in inter-firm power within a supply chain could prevent the implementation of effective supply chain execution.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Maloni and Benton note that until their research, "little power research" had been presented in the supply chain literature.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Using French and Raven's typology of the sources of power in the context of the automotive industry, they aimed to analyse the effects of distinct power strategies on relationships between buyers and sellers, and upon supply chain performance and satisfaction.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] They concluded that "prudent use of power" can be beneficial for both the power source and the power target.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Reverse logistics is the process of managing the return of goods and may be considered as an aspect of "aftermarket customer services".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Any time money is taken from a company's warranty reserve or service logistics budget, one can speak of a reverse logistics operation.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Reverse logistics also includes the process of managing the return of goods from store, which the returned goods are sent back to warehouse and after that either warehouse scrap the goods or send them back to supplier for replacement depending on the warranty of the merchandise.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Successful SCM requires a change from managing individual functions to integrating activities into key supply chain processes.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In an example scenario, a purchasing department places orders as its requirements become known.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The marketing department, responding to customer demand, communicates with several distributors and retailers as it attempts to determine ways to satisfy this demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Information shared between supply chain partners can only be fully leveraged through business process integration, e.g., using electronic data interchange.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Supply chain business process integration involves collaborative work between buyers and suppliers, joint product development, common systems, and shared information.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] According to Lambert and Cooper (2000), operating an integrated supply chain requires a continuous information flow.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] However, in many companies, management has concluded that optimizing product flows cannot be accomplished without implementing a process approach.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Much has been written about demand management.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Customer relationship management concerns the relationship between an organization and its customers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] It also provides the customer with real-time information on scheduling and product availability through interfaces with the company's production and distribution operations.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Effective business process integration in supply chain management requires not only continuous communication, but also strategic coordination across departments and partner companies.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The main reason for this is that it can effectively improve agility.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] At the same time, this integration can help businesses respond quickly to changes in demand and improve customer satisfaction.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Inventory management is concerned with ensuring the right stock at the right levels, in the right place, at the right time and the right cost.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Inventory management entails inventory planning and forecasting: forecasting helps planning inventory.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Strategic plans are drawn up with suppliers to support the manufacturing flow management process and the development of new products.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In firms whose operations extend globally, sourcing may be managed on a global basis.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The desired outcome is a relationship where both parties benefit and a reduction in the time required for the product's design and development.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] (EDI) and internet linkage, to convey possible requirements more rapidly.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] , many of which include the responsibility to coordinate with suppliers on matters of scheduling, supply continuity (inventory), hedging, and research into new sources or programs.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Procurement has recently been recognized as a core source of value, driven largely by the increasing trends to outsource products and services, and the changes in the global ecosystem requiring stronger relationships between buyers and sellers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Here, customers and suppliers must be integrated into the product development process in order to reduce the time to market.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] shorten, the appropriate products must be developed and successfully launched with ever-shorter time schedules in order for firms to remain competitive.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] 3. develop production technology in manufacturing flow to manufacture and integrate into the best supply chain flow for the given combination of product and markets.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Integration of suppliers into the new product development process was shown to have a major impact on product target cost, quality, delivery, and market share.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Tapping into suppliers as a source of innovation requires an extensive process characterized by development of technology sharing, but also involves managing intellectual property issues.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The manufacturing process produces and supplies products to the distribution channels based on past forecasts.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Orders are processes operating on a just-in-time (JIT) basis in minimum lot sizes.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Changes in the manufacturing flow process lead to shorter cycle times (cycle time compression), meaning improved responsiveness and efficiency in meeting customer demand.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] La Londe and Masters found in 1994 research that improved supply chain management and cycle time compression were complementary strategies adopted by forward-looking businesses in the United States.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This concerns the movement of a finished product or service to customers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] In physical distribution, the customer is the final destination of a marketing channel, and the availability of the product or service is a vital part of each channel participant's marketing effort.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] It is also through the physical distribution process that the time and space of customer service become an integral part of marketing.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Thus it links a marketing channel with its customers (i.e., it links manufacturers, wholesalers, and retailers).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] is the function within supply chain management that is responsible for overseeing a company's fleet of vehicles.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This includes not only trucks and vans but also other assets like ships, planes, and specialized machinery.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Modern **fleet management** is a key component of **fleet digitalization**.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] It relies heavily on **telematics** and **vehicle tracking systems** to provide real-time data on vehicle location, driver behavior, and engine diagnostics.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This **telemetry** data is used to optimize routes, schedule predictive maintenance, and enhance the overall visibility and control of the physical distribution network.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This includes not just the outsourcing of the procurement of materials and components, but also the outsourcing of services that traditionally have been provided in-house.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The logic of this trend is that the company will increasingly focus on those activities in the value chain in which it has a distinctive advantage and outsource everything else.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] This movement has been particularly evident in logistics, where the provision of transport, storage, and inventory control is increasingly subcontracted to specialists or logistics partners.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Also, managing and controlling this network of partners and suppliers requires a blend of central and local involvement: strategic decisions are taken centrally, while the monitoring and control of supplier performance and day-to-day liaison with logistics partners are best managed locally.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Experts found a strong relationship from the largest arcs of supplier and customer integration to market share and profitability.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Taking advantage of supplier capabilities and emphasizing a long-term supply chain perspective in customer relationships can both be correlated with a firm's performance.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] As logistics competency becomes a critical factor in creating and maintaining competitive advantage, measuring logistics performance becomes increasingly important, because the difference between profitable and unprofitable operations becomes narrower.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] (1985) noted that firms engaging in comprehensive performance measurement realized improvements in overall productivity.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] internal measures are generally collected and analyzed by the firm, including cost, customer service, productivity, asset measurement, and quality.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] To reduce a company's cost and expenses, warehousing management is concerned with storage, reducing manpower cost, dispatching authority with on time delivery, loading and unloading facilities with proper area, inventory management system etc.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] There are gaps in the literature on supply chain management studies at present.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] A few authors, such as Halldorsson et al., Ketchen and Hult (2006), and Lavassani et al.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] However, the unit of analysis of most of these theories is not the supply chain but rather another system, such as the firm or the supplier-buyer relationship.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Among the few exceptions is the relational view, which outlines a theory for considering dyads and networks of firms as a key unit of analysis for explaining superior individual firm performance (Dyer and Singh, 1998).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The management of supply chains involve a number of specific challenges regarding the organization of relationships among the different partners along the value chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Formal and informal governance mechanisms are central elements in the management of supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] Particular combinations of governance mechanisms may impact the relational dynamics within the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p01] The need for interdisciplinarity in SCM research has been pointed out by academics in the field.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In the study of supply chain management, the concept of centroids has become a useful economic consideration.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In mathematics and physics, a centroid is the arithmetic mean position of all the points in a plane figure.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] For supply chain management, a centroid is a location with a high proportion of a country's population and a high proportion of its manufacturing, generally within 500 mi (805 km).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In the US, two major supply chain centroids have been defined, one near Dayton, Ohio, and a second near Riverside, California.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The centroid near Dayton is particularly important because it is closest to the population center of the US and Canada.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Dayton is within 500 miles of 60% of the US population and manufacturing capacity, as well as 60% of Canada's population.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The region includes the interchange between I-70 and I-75, one of the busiest in the nation, with 154,000 vehicles passing through per day, of which 30–35% are trucks hauling goods.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In addition, the I-75 corridor is home to the busiest north–south rail route east of the Mississippi River.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] A supply chain is the network of all the individuals, organizations, resources, activities and technology involved in the creation and sale of a product.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] A supply chain encompasses everything from the delivery of source materials from the supplier to the manufacturer through to its eventual delivery to the end user.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The supply chain segment involved with getting the finished product from the manufacturer to the consumer is known as the distribution channel.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In 2010, Wal-Mart announced a big change in its sourcing strategy.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Initially, Wal-Mart relied on intermediaries in the sourcing process.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] It bought only 20% of its stock directly, but the rest were bought through the intermediaries.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Therefore, the company came to realize that the presence of many intermediaries in the product sourcing was actually increasing the costs in the supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] To cut these costs, Wal-Mart decided to do away with intermediaries in the supply chain and started direct sourcing of its goods from the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Eduardo Castro-Wright, the then Vice President of Wal-Mart, set an ambitious goal of buying 80% of all Wal-Mart goods directly from the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Walmart started purchasing fruits and vegetables on a global scale, where it interacted directly with the suppliers of these goods.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The company later engaged the suppliers of other goods, such as cloth and home electronics appliances, directly and eliminated the importing agents.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The purchaser, in this case Wal-Mart, can easily direct the suppliers on how to manufacture certain products so that they can be acceptable to the consumers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Thus, Wal-Mart, through direct sourcing, manages to get the exact product quality as it expects, since it engages the suppliers in the producing of these products, hence quality consistency.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Using agents in the sourcing process in most cases lead to inconsistency in the quality of the products, since the agent's source the products from different manufacturers that have varying qualities.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart managed to source directly 80% profit its stock; this has greatly eliminated the intermediaries and cut down the costs between 5-15%, as markups that are introduced by these middlemen in the supply chain are cut.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] This strategy of direct sourcing not only helped Wal-Mart in reducing the costs in the supply chain but also helped in the improvement of supply chain activities through boosting efficiency throughout the entire process.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In other words, direct sourcing reduced the time that takes the company to source and stocks the products in its stock.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The presence of the intermediaries elongated the time in the process of procurement, which sometimes led to delays in the supply of the commodities in the stores, thus, customers finding empty shelves.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart adopted this strategy of sourcing through centralizing the entire process of procurement and sourcing by setting up four global merchandising points for general goods and clothing.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The company instructed all the suppliers to bring their products to these central points that are located in different markets.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The procurement team assesses the quality brought by the suppliers, buys the goods, and distributes them to various regional markets.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The procurement and sourcing at centralized places helped the company to consolidate the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The company has established four centralized points, including an office in Mexico City and Canada.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Just a mere piloting test on combining the purchase of fresh apples across the United States, Mexico, and Canada led to the savings of about 10%.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] As a result, the company intended to increase centralization of its procurement in North America for all its fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Strategic vendor partnerships is another strategy the company is using in the sourcing process.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart realized that in order for it to ensure consistency in the quality of the products it offers to the consumers and also maintain a steady supply of goods in its stores at a lower cost, it had to create strategic vendor partnerships with the suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Wal-Mart identified and selected the suppliers who met its demand and at the same time offered it the best prices for the goods.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] It then made a strategic relationship with these vendors by offering and assuring the long-term and high volume of purchases in exchange for the lowest possible prices.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Thus, the company has managed to source its products from same suppliers as bulks, but at lower prices.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] This enables the company to offer competitive prices for its products in its stores, hence, maintaining a competitive advantage over its competitors whose goods are a more expensive in comparison.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Another sourcing strategy Wal-Mart uses is implementing efficient communication relationships with the vendor networks; this is necessary to improve the material flow.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The company has all the contacts with the suppliers whom they communicate regularly and make dates on when the goods would be needed, so that the suppliers get ready to deliver the goods in time.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The efficient communication between the company's procurement team and the inventory management team enables the company to source goods and fill its shelves on time, without causing delays and empty shelves.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In other words, the company realized that in ensuring a steady flow of the goods into the store, the suppliers have to be informed early enough, so that they can act accordingly to avoid delays in the delivery of goods.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Thus, efficient communication is another tool which Wal-Mart is using to make the supply chain be more efficient and to cut costs.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Cross-docking is another strategy that Wal-Mart is using to cut costs in its supply chain.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Cross-docking is the process of transferring goods directly from inbound trucks to outbound trucks.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] When the trucks from the suppliers arrive at the distribution centers, most of the trucks are not offloaded to keep the goods in the distribution centers or warehouses; they are transferred directly to another truck designated to deliver goods to specific retail stores for sale.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Cross-docking helps in saving the storage costs.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Initially, the company was incurring considerable costs of storing the goods from the suppliers in its warehouses and the distributions centers to await the distribution trucks to the retail stores in various regions.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Tax-efficient supply chain management is a business model that considers the effect of tax in the design and implementation of supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] As the consequence of globalization, cross-national businesses pay different tax rates in different countries.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Due to these differences, they may legally optimize their supply chain and increase profits based on tax efficiency.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain networks are integral to an economy, but their health is dependent on the well-being of the environment and society.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain sustainability is a business issue affecting an organization's supply chain or logistics network, and is frequently quantified by comparison with SECH ratings, which address social, ethical, cultural, and health footprints.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] These build on the triple bottom line incorporating economic, social, and environmental aspects.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The more commonly used ESG terminology represents Environment, Social and Governance.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Because supply chains may account for over 75% of a company's carbon footprint, many organizations are exploring ways to reduce this and thus improve their profile.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] For example, in July 2009, Wal-Mart announced its intentions to create a global sustainability index that would rate products according to the environmental and social impacts of their manufacturing and distribution.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The index is intended to create environmental accountability in Wal-Mart's supply chain and to provide motivation and infrastructure for other retail companies to do the same.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] It has been reported that companies are increasingly taking environmental performance into account when selecting suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] A 2011 survey by the Carbon Trust found that 50% of multinationals expect to select their suppliers based upon carbon performance in the future and 29% of suppliers could lose their places on 'green supply chains' if they do not have adequate performance records on carbon.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In addition to environmental concerns, increased globalization within global supply chains challenges human rights and worker exploitation risks within multinational corporations including forced labor and modern slavery.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Textiles, agriculture, and manufacturing are some of the industries with significant labor exploitation risks.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] There are many different methods governments, corporations, and NGOs use to prevent labor exploitation, including corporate social responsibility, export controls, import bans, and monitoring labor standards.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The US Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, signed into law by President Obama in July 2010, contained a supply chain sustainability provision in the form of the Conflict Minerals law.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The chain of suppliers and vendors to these reporting companies will be expected to provide appropriate supporting information.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Incidents like the 2013 Savar building collapse, with more than 1,100 victims, have led to widespread discussions about corporate social responsibility across global supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Wieland and Handfield (2013) suggest that companies need to audit products and suppliers and that supplier auditing needs to go beyond direct relationships with first-tier suppliers.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] They also demonstrate that visibility needs to be improved if supply cannot be directly controlled and that smart and electronic technologies play a key role to improve visibility.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Finally, they highlight that collaboration with local partners, across the industry and with universities is crucial to successfully managing social responsibility in supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Recent research proposes a two-phase approach for auditing multitier supply networks.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Under this strategy, buyers first audit and drop noncompliant suppliers and then proceed to audit and rectify the remaining ones; when auditing an upper tier, the approach recommends selecting the "least valuable unaudited supplier" as the next candidate for auditing.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Geissdoerfer *et al*. suggest that circular supply chain management "remains a rather unexplored area of research".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Although it has the same goals as supply chain engineering, supply chain management is focused on a more traditional management and business based approach, whereas supply chain engineering is focused on a mathematical model based one.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Consultancies and media expect the performance efficacy of digitizing supply chains to be high.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Additive manufacturing and blockchain technology have emerged as the two technologies with some of the highest economic relevance.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The potential of additive manufacturing is particularly high in the production of spare parts, since its introduction can reduce warehousing costs of slowly rotating spare parts.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Digitizing technology bears the potential to completely disrupt and restructure supply chains and enhance existing production routes.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In comparison, research on the influence of blockchain technology on the supply chain is still in its early stages.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] literature has argued for a considerably long time that the highest performance efficacy is expected in the potential for automatic contract creation.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In addition, traditional supply chain has many drawbacks such as lack of transparency and trust, and some of them can be solved by blockchain technology.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The technological features of blockchains support transparency and traceability of information, as well as high levels of reliability and immutability of records.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] have implemented blockchain-based traceability systems for agricultural and food supply chains in Taiwan.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] That helps traditional supply chain management to be more efficient and reliable.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain systems configure value for those that organize the networks.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Value is the additional revenue over and above the costs of building the network.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Co-creating value and sharing the benefits appropriately to encourage effective participation is a key challenge for any supply system.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Tony Hines defines value as follows: "Ultimately it is the customer who pays the price for service delivered that confirms value and not the producer who simply adds cost until that point".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Global supply chains pose challenges regarding both quantity and value.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] These trends have many benefits for manufacturers because they make possible larger lot sizes, lower taxes, and better environments (e.g., culture, infrastructure, special tax zones, or sophisticated OEM) for their products.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] There are many additional challenges when the scope of supply chains is global.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] This is because with a supply chain of a larger scope, the lead time is much longer, and because there are more issues involved, such as multiple currencies, policies, and laws.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The consequent problems include different currencies and valuations in different countries, different tax laws, different trading protocols, vulnerability to natural disasters and cyber threats, and lack of transparency of cost and profit.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The disruptions in the existing international supply chain networks created by tariff increases in 2024-2025 were quantifiable.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Shipping lines recorded large changes in cargo tonnage and trade routes when manufacturers reviewed the economic feasibility of marketed trade routes.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] According to German shipping company Hapag-Lloyd, one in every three of the planned U.S.-bound shipments in China had been cancelled as a result of tariff announcements.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] These cancellations were one of the more drastic instances of instant supply chain change, providing unused capacity on trans-Pacific paths, and at the same time, placing additional stress on companies to find alternative sourcing deals.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The extent of disruption depended on the sector of the industry, and the most impacted was the labor-intensive manufacturing.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Government officials had economic evaluations that pointed to other wider consequences than direct trade expenses.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The Finance Minister of Indonesia estimated that disruptions related to tariffs would decrease the GDP of the country by 0.3 to 0.5 percentage points.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] These projections represented fears of second-hand effects, such as reduced investment in business and slowed infrastructure development in export-related sectors.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The countries that had high manufacturing export bases were under special pressure to diversify access to markets.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Not every economy had suffered equal adverse effects from the tariff environment.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The increase of Mexican manufacturing exports to the United States was about 9 percent between January and November 2025.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] However, automotive shipments were subject to special duties, whereas the non-automotive manufactured commodities showed better performance with 17% increase over the same period of time.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] This was apparently a result of the reorientation of the supply chain, where production operations moved to areas where preferential trade status was being sustained by the jurisdictions.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Some of the observers were surprised by the pace of such reconfigurations, and this indicated that the supply chain was more flexible than was earlier thought.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Corporate adaptation practices were not just limited to mere geographical relocation.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The documented responses were the reorganization of procurement networks, changes in the import process to streamline the tariff classification, and speedy sourcing activities in the region.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Some multinational companies developed parallel sourcing capacity in two or more locations - a back-up to maintain the flexibility of operations in the face of policy vagaries.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The economic implications of having duplicate supply chains made the long-term sustainability of such methods questionable.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] These changes took place in compressed periods as compared to the conventional redesign of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Whereas major network restructuring normally takes several years to be implemented, tariff-based changes often need to be put in place within quarters.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] This speed challenged organizational agility to change and identified supply chain agility as a more and more important strategic ability.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] It was still a debatable issue whether those changes would continue to exist once the possible cut on tariffs would occur after all.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain professionals play major roles in the design and management of supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In the design of supply chains, they help determine whether a product or service is provided by the firm itself (insourcing) or by another firm elsewhere (outsourcing).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In the management of supply chains, supply chain professionals coordinate production among multiple providers, ensuring that production and transport of goods happen with minimal quality control or inventory problems.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] One goal of a well-designed and maintained supply chain for a product is to successfully build the product at minimal cost.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Such a supply chain could be considered a competitive advantage for a firm.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Beyond design and maintenance of a supply chain itself, supply chain professionals participate in aspects of business that have a bearing on supply chains, such as sales forecasting, quality management, strategy development, customer service, and systems analysis.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Production of a good may evolve over time, rendering an existing supply chain design obsolete.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain professionals need to be aware of changes in production and business climate that affect supply chains and create alternative supply chains as the need arises.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Keeping up with frequent changes in regulation was identified as a particular concern.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Complexity within supply chains has also been highlighted in *Supply Chain Digest* and by Gartner as a perennial challenge.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain consultants may provide expert knowledge in order to assess the productivity of a supply chain and, ideally, to enhance its productivity.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In this regard, firms may either build internal teams of consultants to tackle the issue or engage external ones: companies choose between these two approaches taking into consideration various factors.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The use of external consultants is a common practice among companies.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The whole consulting process generally involves the analysis of the entire supply chain process, including the countermeasures or correctives to take to achieve a better overall performance.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Supply chain professionals need to have knowledge of managing supply chain functions such as transportation, warehousing, inventory management, and production planning.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In the past, supply chain professionals emphasized logistics skills, such as knowledge of shipping routes, familiarity with warehousing equipment and distribution center locations and footprints, and a solid grasp of freight rates and fuel costs.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] More recently, supply chain management extends to logistical support across firms and management of global supply chains.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] A shortage of skilled supply chain professionals was highlighted in a study by the Massachusetts Institute of Technology published in 2010, which highlighted plentiful supply of staff with "narrow technical skillsets" but shortages in the numbers of job applicants with "broader business skills".
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Individuals working in supply chain management can attain professional certification by passing an exam developed by a third party certification organization.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The purpose of certification is to guarantee a certain level of expertise in the field.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The knowledge needed to pass a certification exam may be gained from several sources.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Some knowledge may come from college courses, but most of it is acquired from a mix of on-the-job learning experiences, attending industry events, learning best practices with their peers, and reading books and articles in the field.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Certification organizations may provide certification workshops tailored to their exams.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] In the same ranking, the following European universities rank high: Cranfield School of Management, Vlerick Business School, INSEAD, Cambridge University, Eindhoven University of Technology, London Business School and Copenhagen Business School.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] APICS' certification is called *Certified Supply Chain Professional*, or CSCP, and ISCEA's certification is called the *Certified Supply Chain Manager* (CSCM), CISCM (Chartered Institute of Supply Chain Management) awards certificate as *Chartered Supply Chain Management Professional* (CSCMP).
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] Another, the Institute for Supply Management, is developing one called the *Certified Professional in Supply Management* (CPSM) focused on the procurement and sourcing areas of supply chain management.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The Supply Chain Management Association (SCMA) is the main certifying body for Canada with the designations having global reciprocity.
[src:supply-chain-software/supply-chain-management-p02] The designation Supply Chain Management Professional (SCMP) is the title of the supply chain leadership designation.
